# Machine learning on Titanic disaster

Author: Paul Bustios

## Table of contents

1. Introduction
- Objective
- Requirements
- Getting the data
- Analyzing the data
- Selecting a model
- Testing the model
- Conclusion

## 1. Introduction

> The sinking of the RMS Titanic is one of the most infamous shipwrecks in history. On April 15, 1912, during her maiden voyage, the Titanic sank after colliding with an iceberg, killing 1502 out of 2224 passengers and crew. This tragedy shocked the international community and led to better safety regulations for ships. One of the reasons that the shipwreck led to such loss of life was that there were not enough lifeboats for the passengers and crew. Although there was some element of luck involved in surviving the sinking, some groups of people were more likely to survive than others, such as women, children, and the upper-class. -- From: [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic)

![titanic](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/RMS_Titanic_3.jpg/320px-RMS_Titanic_3.jpg "RMS Titanic") RMS Titanic. Image source: [Wikipedia](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:RMS_Titanic_3.jpg)

## 2. Objective

This notebook is intended to show the common steps present in a machine learning problem. For that, we are going to setup a try to predict if a person had survived to the sinking based on the information contained in the [Titanic dataset](http://biostat.mc.vanderbilt.edu/wiki/pub/Main/DataSets/titanic.html).

## 3. Requirements

To be able to execute the code in this notebook, it is necessary to have installed Python 3.5 and the following libraries:

- Matplotlib >= 1.5.1
- Pandas >= 0.18.0
- Scikit-learn >= 0.17.1
- Seaborn >= 0.7.0

If you already have installed other versions and want to maintain them and your system stability or just want to avoid problems managing dependencies, you can use [Miniconda](http://conda.pydata.org/miniconda.html), a reduced version of [Anaconda](https://www.continuum.io/downloads) Python distribution, with Python 3.5. Once installed Miniconda, you can install the libraries using the command:

    conda install pandas scikit-learn seaborn

This command will install the latest versions of these libraries and will keep them along with Python 3.5 in a virtual environment completely independent of system libraries.

## 4. Getting the data

First, we have to download the Titanic dataset from <http://biostat.mc.vanderbilt.edu/DataSets>, specifically the `titanic3.csv` file. This dataset contains information of 1309 passengers arranged in 14 variables. You can find more information about this dataset [here](http://biostat.mc.vanderbilt.edu/wiki/pub/Main/DataSets/titanic3info.txt).

paragraphs.title: Downloading the data
paragraphs.text:
%sh

cd /tmp

data=titanic3.csv
rm -f $data
wget "http://biostat.mc.vanderbilt.edu/wiki/pub/Main/DataSets/titanic3.csv"

if [ -e $data ]
then
    echo "\"$data\" file downloaded successfully in /tmp/$data"
else
    echo "There was a problem downloading the file $data"
fi

%md

## 5. Analyzing the data

The objective of this step is to know the data and improve our understanding of the problem. Let's load the data and take a look at it using [Pandas](http://pandas.pydata.org/). Each row represents a passenger on the Titanic and each column contains some information about them. The columns are:

1. **pclass**: the class the passenger was in (1 = first class, 2 = second class, 3 = third class).
- **survived**: whether the passenger survived (0 = no, 1 = yes). We will predict this value.
- **name**: the name of the passenger.
- **sex**: the gender of the passenger (male, female).
- **age**: the age of the passenger. It can be fractional if the age is less than one or is estimated.
- **sibsp**: the number of siblings and spouses the passenger had on board.
- **parch**: the number of parents and children the passenger had on board.
- **ticket**: the ticket number of the passenger.
- **fare**: how much the passenger paid for the ticker.
- **cabin**: which cabin the passenger was in.
- **embarked**: where the passenger boarded the Titanic (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton).
- **boat**: for survivors, the lifeboat identifier from which they were known to be rescued.
- **body**: for victims, the body identification number.
- **home.dest**: passenger's home/destination.

%md 

Now, we are going to divide the data into train and test subsets. For that we are going to use [scikit-learn](http://scikit-learn.org/). Scikit-learn is a Python module for machine learning with many other utilities to deal with common tasks in machine learning.

We have set `random_state = 1` in `train_test_split` function to guarantee that the split will be always the same for reproducible results.

paragraphs.title: Dividing the data into training and testing subsets
paragraphs.text:
%python

from sklearn.cross_validation import train_test_split

# We set random_state=1 to guarantee that the split will 
# be always the same for reproducible results
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    titanic.drop(["survived"], axis=1),  # X
    titanic["survived"],  # y
    test_size=0.32,
    random_state=1,
    stratify=titanic["survived"])

print("Train set size: %s" % X_train.shape[0])
print("Test set size: %s" % X_test.shape[0])

Hereinafter, all the changes we make in the data will be only in the training set, and we will leave the test set to the end to measure the accuracy of our machine learning model.

Since columns **boat** and **body** determine directly if a person survived or did not, and columns **name**, **cabin**, **ticket**, **home.dest** are specific passenger features and unlikely to tell us much without some domain knowledge, we are going to remove such columns and print the number of observations we have in the remaining columns and their type.

You will notice that the **age** column has a count of 714 non-null data, **fare** and **embarked** columns have 889 and all the other columns have a count of 890. This indicates that there are missing values.

paragraphs.text:
%md

## 6. Selecting a model

Now that all our data is numeric, we are ready to select and apply a machine learning model to predict the survivors. There are many models, so what should we choose? Since our problem consist in predicting a value which can be zero or one, we are going to choose a linear model, specifically a Logistic Regression model. But, why a logistic regression model? We choose it for two reasons:

- Before to try a sofisticated model, we have to start with the simplest. A simple model is not always a bad model.
- Logistic regression predicts categorical values, and that's what we want.

paragraphs.title: 10-fold cross-validation on Logistic Regression
paragraphs.text:
%python

from sklearn.cross_validation import cross_val_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

logreg = LogisticRegression()
scores = cross_val_score(logreg, X_train, y_train, cv=10)
print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (scores.mean(), scores.std() * 2))

paragraphs.title: 10-fold cross-validation on Random Forest
paragraphs.text:
%python

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, 
                            n_estimators=40,
                            min_samples_split=4,
                            min_samples_leaf=2)
scores = cross_val_score(rf, X_train, y_train, cv=10)
print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (scores.mean(), scores.std() * 2))

%md 

## 7. Testing the model

Now, let's test our models. But, before that, we have to apply all the transformations we made on the training set to the test set.

paragraphs.title: Data cleaning on test set
paragraphs.text:
%python 

X_test.drop(["name", "cabin", "ticket", "boat", "body", "home.dest"], axis=1, inplace=True)

X_test["embarked"].fillna("S", inplace=True)

embarked_codes = {"S": 0, "C": 1, "Q": 2}  # new values for embarked column

paragraphs.text:

logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)
score_pred = logreg.score(X_test, y_test)

print("Accuracy: %0.2f" % (score_pred))

print("Accuracy: %0.2f" % (score_pred))

paragraphs.title: Feature ranking in Logistic Regression
paragraphs.text:
%python

import numpy as np

lr_importances = np.abs(logreg.coef_)[0]
lr_indices = np.argsort(lr_importances)[::-1]

# Print the feature ranking
print("Feature ranking:")

lr_labels = []
for f in range(X_train.shape[1]):
    lr_labels.append(X_train.columns.values[lr_indices[f]])
    print("%d) %s (%f)" % (f + 1, lr_labels[f], lr_importances[lr_indices[f]]))

paragraphs.title: Feature ranking in Random Forest
paragraphs.text:
%python 

importances = rf.feature_importances_
std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in rf.estimators_], axis=0)
indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

# Print the feature ranking
print("Feature ranking:")

labels = []
for f in range(X_train.shape[1]):
    labels.append(X_train.columns.values[indices[f]])
    print("%d) %s (%f)" % (f + 1, labels[f], importances[indices[f]]))

paragraphs.title: Feature importances in Logistic Regression
paragraphs.text:

sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize": (6, 4)})

plt.bar(range(X_train.shape[1]), lr_importances[lr_indices],
        color="r", align="center")
plt.xticks(range(X_train.shape[1]), lr_labels)
plt.xlim([-1, X_train.shape[1]])

plt.figure()

        color="r", yerr=std[indices], align="center")

%md

## 8. Conclusion

By history, we know that women had priority to be saved and, as a matter of fact, this feature is the most important in both the logistic regression and the random forest. Another important feature is the age, in the case of logistic regression, it is not as important as in the random forest. That's probably why random forest performed better than logistic regression.
